title: For Sale:  WWII M1918A2 BAR Browning Automatic Rifle
postcontent: For sale is my M1918A2 BAR. Complete parts guns are hard to find, and do not include barrels. This is a complete parts kit mounted on a Philadelphia Ordnance 80% machined receiver. Barrel is marked 'NE-7' over the flaming ordnance bomb, and the month of barrel manufacture, 7-43. New England Arms Corp. was the rarest of the WWII BAR manufacturers. Receiver is not a "dummy", but is completed to 80% of the machine operations needed to operate. All external machining is done, as is much of the internal as it accepts the buttstock and buffer, cocking handle, etc., which are already mounted on it. This is the best BAR receiver made, machined from 8620 steel plate. Currently classified as a "non-gun" by ATF, but can be finished into a shooter. I have had estimates of $500-$700 to complete it as a semi-auto rifle. Properly licensed individuals could complete the receiver as a full-auto. However, it is a "non-gun" in it's current state which makes it legal to ship to any state. The rest of the rifle is shown in the pics. Includes repro leather BAR sling and Technical Manual. Display it as is, complete the machining or hire someone to do it, and save a bunch of money off what these sell for. I will provide buyer with contact info of company that can complete this as a semi-auto. I will include the ATF letter, Info sheet from Philadelphia Ordnance, and BAR receiver machinist drawings. I can include a few BAR magazines if you need them and are paying my asking price. I may trade for a current manufactured Colt, Armalite, Windham Weaponry, older Colt SP1, or other well made AR-15 type rifle plus cash. This is a good deal, as these are rare, and do not often include WWII barrels. Display or complete, either way a great addition to a WWII collection.

title: For Sale:  M1C Sniper Garand
postcontent:
This is the rarest of the M1 Garand variants. This rifle is a WWII produced M1C Garand sniper rifle. I purchased this from a CMP auction in 2006, and it will come with the certificate of authenticity from CMP identifying it as a genuine M1C rifle, as well as a letter of authenticity from the nation's leading M1C expert. There are no import marks. It is still a legitimate M1C as identified by serious collectors, as the holes for the scope bracket have merely been filled. Though the actual amount of WWII M1Cs converted in this manner are unknown, it is thought to be near 4 thousand that were converted. Many of these were destroyed during the Carter/Clinton years by "Captain Crunch", making this the rarest of the M1 variants. 
My recommendation to any buyer would be to leave the rifle as it currently is, as it is a rare variant. However, there are several reputable M1 gunsmiths who can restore this at a very reasonable cost. I will include a scope bracket that I believe to be an original parkerized replacement. The bracket has machine marks, indicating it is not cast. There are no serial numbers on this bracket, as it has never been mounted to a rifle. Value of this alone is 300-500. The screws and taper pins are still available from the original WWII/Korean War maker of the sniper component items, Griffen and Howe. Many of the M1C rifles you will see are fakes made from regular rifles, with repro or newly made scope brackets installed. They will not pass the scrutiny of collectors for several reasons. 
During the Korean War Armory level rebuild program, this WWII sniper rifle,serial #359xxxx, was rebuilt, and returned to normal M1 configuration, though the holes on the left side of the receiver for the screws and pins that hold the bracket are clearly visible, another 100% sign that this is a legitimate M1C.  Finish appears to be original, definitely not ugly Greek black parkerizing which most of the M1Cs bear today, as those are more recent CMP sales rifles returned from Greece.  Chamber is in the white. The Muzzle Wear, or MW of this rifle is near new, just over 2, indicating this was not fired much. Several new old stock barrels wil guage at or near what this will. Barrel is dated 1-53, correct for the SA-52 rebuild timeframe which ran from approximately from July '51 to June '53. Barrel is marked correctly, SA D6535448, with date of 1 53. Wood is nice USGI walnut, not current repro. Has a slight gouge in stock just behind the DAS cartouche, and two dings on the rear handguard, front handguard has a barely noticeable ding as well. Has serifed firing proof 'P' and 1/2" DAS cartouche strongly present.  Operating Rod is marked D35382. Bolt is 2828712-SA, with heat lot code of W10B. Trigger housing is D28290-12-SA, with -5 SA hammer and -6 SA safety. Stamped trigger guard. Rear sight elevation is SA, windage is BME. Gas cylinder is wide base with much original finish, lock is WWII type. Screw is late, P followed by octogon symbol. Front sight is SA with late type screw. Other parts not mentioned are late type, though the follower is early. I inspected the M1C rifles at the CMP south store last August, and few looked as nice as this rifle. One would have to get their highest grade, at a cost of $3000.00, and still not match the quality of this rifle. Most of the M1Cs there with similar barrel quality did not have USGI wood and had the ugly Greek black parkerizing on them, ruining the value as a US martial collectible. With original scope, mount, cheekpiece, and flash hider these sell for $6500.00-$7500.00 on the collector market. Restore this rifle to original configuration, or leave it as the most rare variant of the M1. I would consider a partial trade plus cash of a good AR-15 rifle by Windham Weaponry, Colt, Armalite, or an older Colt SP1. Please don't hesitate to ask if you have more questions or would like to see more pictures. Thank you.

title: For Sale:  PTR-91 15 20-Rd Mags
location: North Fayetteville/Raleigh/Durham, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Offering is a PTR model 91. This rifle was born when our Fed gov’t decided in Regulation ATF 922R that any new firearm could not have more than 10 imported parts in it. At the time the Heckler and Koch model 91 chambered in 7.62 NATO was one of the most popular rifles around and for good reason…

They run like tanks and are very accurate!

This is the civilian version of the German G3 design that has been used by their military since the 1950’s. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heckler_%26_Koch_G3

After the ban on imports, JLD industries bought the engineering and machining from HK to manufacture the model 91 here in the states. These rifles have had several evolutions since the original offering and are rock solid performers. here is the current model listing:
http://www.ptr91.com/rifles
Here are the specs for this particular variation:

18” Button-rifled heavy target barrel in 1 in 12 right hand twist
Semi-auto recoil operated
20 rd box magazine fed
Rotary diopter rear sight with bullet drop compensation set for 100,200,300 and 400 yards
The rifle comes with 15 Magazines, a Brugger and Thomet Picatinny rail mount for optics mount (150 bucks on its own), hard case, sight tool and manual

Bolt and trigger group are manufactured by HK, all other parts are JLD
The trigger is pretty darned good for a rifle of this type
Rifle has about 1000 rounds put down the pipe in its lifetime

THis is a serious rifle for serious shooters,  you can have a 5.56 mousegun or a 7.62 MBR.  Take your pick!  Price on this rifle is firm.  If no serious takers appear, it goes on gunbroker where they are going for the price I've quoted WITHOUT the mags!

postcontent:
Up for sale is a S&W Model 10-5 with a pinned and tapered barrel. As you can see in the photos, it is not perfect. It does have wear on the bluing - most of which I put on it myself using it as a carry gun. It does have an unusual wearing in the bluing on a small part of the cylinder (see photo). 

On the other hand - the performance of this revolver is unlike any other S&W I have ever held. The trigger is absolute butter (in both single and double action). I have never felt a smoother trigger in any other S&W revolver I have ever held. It is also an extremely accurate pistol with a very strong bore.

I think this would make an excellent candidate to take advantage of S&W's re-bluing services. If this was done, it would be an absolutely perfect gun. I've done some unofficial research on this revolver and it's serial number puts it being made sometime in 1968. title: For Sale:  M14 M1A 308 7.62 Israeli Sniper Rile Parts Kit
postcontent: Israeli Defense Force M14 sniper rifle parts kit.This is not a complete rifle. It is the stock, scope mount, scope, and bipod from an Israel modified US M14 rifle. A Sringfield Armory, Fulton Armory, Norinco, Polyteck, Smith Enterprize, or LRB M1A will work with these parts. The parts were imported by Springfield Armory and I bought them at Camp Perry during the Nationals in the 80's. The Israeli Defense Force modified US M14 Rifles for sniper use.The issue M14 fiberglass stock Had a high comb, rubber recoil pad, side swivels, and a sling stud added. The comb put riflemans eye in line with the scope. The IDF soldier did not have to duck tape foam padding to stocks as was done with a lot of US M21 sniper rifles. Recoil pad was not slippery like the M14 butt plate.The side swivels made for ease of sling carry. They also positioned sling for ease to grasp sling and support rifle on forearm during crawl. The addition of sling stud provided a mounting point for the Harris bipod. The bipod used is a commercial Harris. The IDF designed a heavy duty steel one point anchor scope mount like the first generation US M14 mount. There unique mounting screw locking mechanism stayed tight. The steel "t" slot ribs that engage the grooves in the receiver did not wear and distort under recoil like on our aluminum M14 mounts. The IDF mounts locked securely and maintain zero as compared to first generation US mounts. The scope in this kit is the Israeli "NIMROD" 6X40 with range finding reticle and bullet drop compensator for the US M118 Match Ammunition. The IDF did not bed the actions like our M21 rifles. This stock could easily be bedded to your rifle or left original. Springfield Armory built rifles with these parts. If you do an internet search you can find info on these rifles. I saw pictures were the stocks had been painted with krinkle coat paint and looked very good. The stock is good condition as is. The Harris bipod { not an import copy] is in good condition. The scope mount is in good condition. It has integral 26MM rings. The scope is in good condition with good optics. There are some nicks in the paint. I have not test ed the scope. From what I have read they are a hardy scope built for military service. The Kahles ZF 69 6X42 was also used by the IDF. No FFL required as listing is for parts only. Us sales to US citizens and buyer must insure you can legally own these parts. Thanks for checking this listing. Insured shipping will be $20.00 for CONUS.
